We even asked for additional water cups and he brought empty cups. -the buss staff guys were busting their tails while the wait staff was literally standing around. Tremendous burgers and fries in a characterful old space right across from the main Harvard campus. We stopped in and had a great lunch. The make your own burger option was appreciated and yielded tasty, greasy cheeseburgers. Seemed like a classic college spot. I would happily go back.
My new favorite burger place.  The onion rings are the best.  The slaw is how I like it.  The burger was cooked exactly how I like it rare.  It was great.
This place is first-rate and roomy, the food was delightful and the prices were very affordable. fast, productive service and very amiable staff members. Recommended.

Undercooked, soggy, and not worth the price! I got my food delivered, so some of the sogginess could be contributed to that, but my burger was undercooked regardless of getting it delivered. The fries and onion rings were soggy and had no body. The Diet Coke I ordered was also wrong, as I received a Coke instead. For the price and online praise, I expected great food, but got a disappointing end to my day instead. I would not recommend this restaurant to anyone I know.

My first time here. I came to visit Boston and had a taste for a burger. This place is very close to the Havard subway exit. I tried the Vaccine. It has ghost pepper Cheese on it! 😱 I loved it! The Burgers are very tasty and I highly recommend stopping there if you are in town.  Just 25mins from the Airport. To my aviation family, If you have a long layover and want a burger, explore the Boston Public Transit and stop by here. You won't regret it.  Fresh Lemonade Too!  The food was great and so was the service( s/o to Willy, a server).

They reopened a couple of weeks ago after Cambridge loosened up on restaurant restrictions but did not miss a beat as their quality and good humor remains intact. They offer both indoor and outdoor dining. The burger was delicious as usual, and we always go with their onion rings.  We don't even bother to order onion rings at any other restaurant.  For drinks it's usually a traditional fresh lime rickey, though you can get a raspberry lime rickey as well. Bartley's is up for sale and who knows what the future may bring, so get there soon before yet another part of what makes Harvard Sq great vanishes.

This place is legendary and hyped by countless famous people. Allow me to separate the legend and hype from reality. Mr. Bartley's Gourmet Burgers is living on past glory. That is if they ever even had any. They have shoehorned so many tables inside this small space it is like eating in a High School cafeteria. I had the “SECRETARY OF STATE WILLIAM GALVIN” Not a bad 9 dollar hamburger. The only problem was they charged me $13.75 then wanted 1 dollar extra for BBQ sauce. You remember in Pulp Fiction when Travolta could not believe that a milkshake cost 5 dollars? Well, here they call them Frappes and get 9 bucks for them. I will say that the homemade onion rings were the highlight of the meal.

The food was great and the service was better.   Even though it has been around for a long time, they act as if they are new with burgers named for people in current events, I had the Andrew Yang.  The onion rings were excellent.  Fun place to go.  Lots of famous people sat there.

I am the third generation of my family to eat here. Let me let that set in. Third generation. My grandfather ate here when he arrived in the us from Egypt and my father ate here when he studied at the Kennedy law school. The onion rings are divine and not loaded with grease. The lim Rickies are refreshing and arguably my favorite drink. And the burgers How can i ever put these flavors in words You wont find a better burger in new england... guaranteed. The simple blend of meat creates a nice juicy patty that will make even the most hardcore burger fans  mouth water in anticipation. This is an essential cornerstone to the harvard square experience and you can bet that i wont be the last generation of my family to eat here

They even have a large variety of "frappes" which are more like thinner milkshakes, and quite tasty. The menu changes with the political and pop cultural references, so be sure to check out a recent menu if you're looking before you go. Great place, Ben says Check it Out.

I feel Mr. Bartley's is significantly overrated.   A good burger, though my medium was more medium rare.  The onion rings and fries were also good, but certainly nothing exceptional.  My three  adult children and I  arrived  and they sat us at an 8 top, even though there were several 4 tops available and the restaurant was no more than 20% full.   The manager then asked us not to spread out because they can fill up quickly.  I am a bigger guy with wide shoulders and we felt sort of needlessly packed in.    The manager was sort of sheepish in asking us to squeeze together, and we quickly complied.   Service was acceptable but not great.  A lot of "promotion" with clever burger names and "famous people" signs of where they sat - somewhat entertaining, but not why I came to eat at Bartley's.   No bathrooms -- I don't think I have ever been to a restaurant without bathrooms,  though there was a bathroom option available next door.  All in in all, a solid 3 but clearly nowhere near a 5.
Expensive, crowded, but good. A bit fancier menu than I need.

Mr. Bartley's has an expansive menu of burgers; I try to get a new one every time I go and they're always great, from the standard to the experimental. The milkshakes (I'm from Jersey, and I call them milkshakes, not 'frappes') are incredible, as it the clam chowder. I try to be stingy with my 5-stars, and have no qualms about dishing one out here.

After a tour of Harvard, we came here for lunch on the recommendation of our tour guide. We got there on the early side, and it was a good thing, because by the time we left, it was packed. They make fun of politicians and current events in the menu descriptions, but it's okay, because they make fun of everyone. The food was solid, and they gave us  generous portions. My husband and I had The Northeastern, which was a turkey sandwich with bacon. They piled the turkey on. We had more than enough french fries. Our son got a cheeseburger, which he enjoyed.  The service was okay, nothing extra special. The prices were reasonable for a burger / sandwich joint in Cambridge Massachusetts. I would definitely recommend Mr. Bartley's.
